30:["$","ul","ul-18",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":["MIT Moral Machine Study (2018): 2.3M participants, 233 countries. Findings:","\n",["$","ul","ul-0",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":"Cross-cultural convergence: Prefer to save more lives (utilitarian)"}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":"Significant divergence: Western vs. East Asian vs. Islamic-majority countries differ on pedestrian vs. passenger priority"}],"\n",["$","li","li-2",{"children":"All cultures prefer sparing children over elderly; few show gender preferences"}],"\n",["$","li","li-3",{"children":"[Awad et al., 2018, Nature]"}],"\n"]}],"\n"]}],"\n"]}]
31:["$","p","p-21",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Engineering approaches to the dilemma"}],":"]}]
32:["$","ul","ul-19",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":"Deontological: Hard rules (never deliberately harm occupants; always brake to minimize impact). Simple, verifiable. May not minimize total harm."}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":"Utilitarian: Minimize expected casualties. Requires probability estimates and value judgments on human lives."}],"\n",["$","li","li-2",{"children":"Contractarian (Rawlsian): Choose policy you'd accept behind a veil of ignorance (not knowing which role you'd play). Favors distributional fairness."}],"\n"]}]
33:["$","p","p-22",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Current industry position"}],": Most manufacturers encode deontological rules (always attempt to stop; never deliberately harm any party). Explicit harm allocation is avoided for legal and reputational reasons."]}]
